  "prompt": "Why are Indians not referred as \"Asians\", when India is a part of Asia?",
  "response": "The use of the term \"Asian\" to refer to people often varies depending on regional and cultural contexts. In many Western countries, particularly in the United States and the United Kingdom, the term \"Asian\" is commonly associated with people from East Asian countries such as China, Japan, Korea, and sometimes Southeast Asian countries like Vietnam, Thailand, and the Philippines. This association has historical roots in immigration patterns and the ways in which different communities have been categorized.\n\nIndia is indeed a part of Asia, and people from India are technically Asians. However, in practice, people from India (as well as from Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, and Nepal) are often specifically referred to as \"South Asians\" to distinguish them from East Asians. This distinction helps to avoid confusion and acknowledges the diverse cultures and identities within the broader continent of Asia.\n\nIn some contexts, you might hear people from India referred to as Asians, but in many places, \"Asian\" has become shorthand for East Asian, and \"South Asian\" is used to refer to individuals from the Indian subcontinent. This usage is not universal and can vary between different regions and communities.",
